wants me dead, mister.

233
00:25:45,128 --> 00:25:48,673
- Yet here I am.
- All right, smart ass, let's cut the bullshit.

234
00:25:49,007 --> 00:25:52,761
You cooperate and we'll get you
transferred to a minimum-security facility.

235
00:25:52,844 --> 00:25:54,471
That's our deal.

236
00:25:54,554 --> 00:25:57,849
And that's your only chance
to walk out of this place in one piece.

237
00:25:57,933 --> 00:26:00,977
That's a one-time offer.
Now take it or leave it.

238
00:26:01,394 --> 00:26:04,314
Stuff it then,
as many fucking times as you like.

239
00:26:04,731 --> 00:26:07,317
Pardon the language. I've been in prison.

240
00:26:20,372 --> 00:26:23,750
All right, what will it take
for you to help us?

241
00:26:25,836 --> 00:26:29,297
First, I'd have to be convinced
Isabella would be kept safe.

242
00:26:29,423 --> 00:26:31,007
Done.

243
00:26:31,842 --> 00:26:33,427
Then you'd have to let me go.

244
00:26:33,510 --> 00:26:35,929
Back to Ireland, a free man.

245
00:26:36,346 --> 00:26:38,473
Out of the question.

246
00:26:40,100 --> 00:26:43,728
Besides gunrunning, you're a known killer
of British government personnel.

247
00:26:43,812 --> 00:26:46,356
And all the women
and children you've blown up.

248
00:26:46,440 --> 00:26:49,651
It's not my war. I was never a bomber.

249
00:26:49,734 --> 00:26:52,737
I don't see the distinction.
You still took human lives.

250
00:26:52,821 --> 00:26:56,700
The distinction is I killed in a war.
Now I want to go home. Simple as that.

251
00:26:56,783 --> 00:26:58,118
Simple for you, perhaps.

252
00:26:58,201 --> 00:27:01,455
Even in Russia, soldiers go home
when the treaty's signed, nyet?

253
00:27:01,538 --> 00:27:04,291
That's not gonna happen. Sorry.

254
00:27:06,877 --> 00:27:09,129
All right, just the chance then.

255
00:27:10,672 --> 00:27:13,133
Your best efforts to get me free.

256
00:27:13,884 --> 00:27:15,969
I'll settle for your word on it.

257
00:27:17,763 --> 00:27:19,848
Sorry.

258
00:27:23,059 --> 00:27:25,687
So the Jackal's after your director, is he?

259
00:27:25,979 --> 00:27:28,148
Tell him to get his affairs in order...

260
00:27:28,231 --> 00:27:29,983
...because nobody can save him now.

261
00:27:30,066 --> 00:27:33,528
Nobody except me. Because I met him.

262
00:27:37,908 --> 00:27:40,118
Yeah, didn't I mention it?

263
00:27:52,089 --> 00:27:56,009
I can identify him by his face,
given the opportunity...

264
00:27:56,301 --> 00:27:58,470
...but more importantly, by his methods.

265
00:28:00,680 --> 00:28:03,433
So you can leave Isabella out of this.

266
00:28:04,101 --> 00:28:05,977
Did you work with him?

267
00:28:06,061 --> 00:28:08,688
With him? No. No way.

268
00:28:11,399 --> 00:28:13,652
Do you have a problem with this man?

269
00:28:15,695 --> 00:28:18,115
That's between him and me.

270
00:28:23,495 --> 00:28:26,915
Isabella Zancona
is the only confirmed contact we have...

271
00:28:26,998 --> 00:28:29,167
...and we will find her.

272
00:28:29,418 --> 00:28:32,045
With or without your help.

273
00:28:32,337 --> 00:28:34,214
Okay.

274
00:28:36,633 --> 00:28:39,719
I want three things.
One: Get me out of here.

275
00:28:39,845 --> 00:28:43,849
- I'm no use to you sitting here on my ass.
- What's to keep you from taking off?

276
00:28:43,932 --> 00:28:45,851
Nothing.

277
00:28:46,184 --> 00:28:48,103
Except I give you my word.

278
00:28:49,563 --> 00:28:52,774
Two: I go with you to meet Isabella.

279
00:28:53,525 --> 00:28:55,152
Why?

280
00:28:55,986 --> 00:28:58,113
I want to see her, is all.

281
00:29:01,658 --> 00:29:03,785
And the third thing?

282
00:29:05,078 --> 00:29:07,080
A decent razor.

283
00:29:11,460 --> 00:29:13,170
Here's how it'll go, Mulqueen.

284
00:29:13,253 --> 00:29:16,798
You will be searched on a random
schedule. If we turn up a paper clip...

285
00:29:16,882 --> 00:29:21,094
...that hasn't been authorized, I'll send
you back. Same for using the phone.

286
00:29:21,178 --> 00:29:24,431
- What? You don't trust me?
- As far as I can throw you.

287
00:29:24,514 --> 00:29:26,475
But I have little choice.

288
00:29:26,558 --> 00:29:29,603
If you've got any thoughts
about an IRA snatch...

289
00:29:29,728 --> 00:29:31,813
...we'll shoot to kill, them and you.

290
00:29:31,897 --> 00:29:34,900
And not necessarily in that order.
Understand?

291
00:29:34,983 --> 00:29:36,902
I heard you.

292
00:29:37,235 --> 00:29:39,988
Go along and we'll get along.

293
00:29:49,623 --> 00:29:51,958
I'm gonna keep a real good eye on you.

294
00:29:56,671 --> 00:29:58,632
Miss Koslova, is it?

295
00:30:05,847 --> 00:30:08,058
What would your first name be then?

296
00:30:08,934 --> 00:30:10,560
Major.

297
00:30:11,311 --> 00:30:13,563
Major Koslova.

298
00:30:20,570 --> 00:30:22,739
A wee bit rusty, that's all.

299
00:30:38,588 --> 00:30:41,883
Subassembly of titanium,
as light as the stresses will allow.

300
00:30:42,884 --> 00:30:45,303
The arm's got to traverse 270 degrees.

301
00:30:45,387 --> 00:30:48,223
Feed and drive mechanisms
run on 210 amp servos.

302
00:30:48,306 --> 00:30:51,184
The whole thing's has to run off 12-volt DC.

303
00:30:51,852 --> 00:30:54,062
Yeah, it's a car battery. That's cool.

304
00:30:54,146 --> 00:30:58,066
- How much weight is the arm supporting?
- Fifty-five kilograms.

305
00:30:58,233 --> 00:31:01,278
It's a big fucker, yeah?

306
00:31:01,528 --> 00:31:03,280
Hey, you want one?

307
00:31:03,363 --> 00:31:04,781
No.

308
00:31:05,824 --> 00:31:08,243
I'm gonna want this in eight days.

309
00:31:08,535 --> 00:31:10,120
I can do that.

310
00:31:11,997 --> 00:31:13,582
How much?

311
00:31:15,709 --> 00:31:18,044
Well, the titanium's gonna be a problem.

312
00:31:18,128 --> 00:31:22,299
It's a listed material up here.
It's gonna take time, a little more money.

313
00:31:23,008 --> 00:31:24,843
$50,000?

314
00:31:28,555 --> 00:31:32,684
I mean, like, $40,000.

315
00:31:35,645 --> 00:31:38,064
All right. Half now, half on delivery.

316
00:31:39,524 --> 00:31:42,527
This sucker's definitely
gonna kick some ass, yeah?

317
00:31:45,155 --> 00:31:46,740
Get this straight.

318
00:31:46,948 --> 00:31:50,660
When you finish this unit, you'll turn over
the plans and scrap material.

319
00:31:50,744 --> 00:31:54,706
You'll forget about Charlie Murdock
and the tech specs on these plans.

320
00:31:55,415 --> 00:31:57,584
Shit, man, I'm cool.

321
00:31:57,667 --> 00:31:59,628
Relax.

322
00:32:01,755 --> 00:32:03,507
All right.

323
00:32:33,203 --> 00:32:34,955
Are you nervous?

324
00:32:37,999 --> 00:32:41,420
Eight years. That's a lifetime, isn't it?

325
00:32:43,630 --> 00:32:45,298
Hello.

326
00:32:45,882 --> 00:32:47,884
- Mr. Decker, is it?
- Yes.

327
00:32:47,968 --> 00:32:50,887
Hello there. I'm Declan Mulqueen.

328
00:32:51,054 --> 00:32:54,307
This is Major Koslova.

329
00:32:54,391 --> 00:32:56,393
- How do you do?
- Hi.

330
00:32:56,852 --> 00:32:58,937
We'd like to speak to your wife.

331
00:33:00,564 --> 00:33:02,983
Someone to see you.

332
00:33:41,146 --> 00:33:43,523
I'll take the kids out back.

333
00:33:48,361 --> 00:33:50,572
My beautiful Irish...

334
00:34:03,960 --> 00:34:06,338
They let me out to ask you something.

335
00:34:07,964 --> 00:34:12,010
Sir, I was thinking maybe we could
use the Zancona woman as insurance...

336
00:34:12,302 --> 00:34:14,846
...in case Mulqueen gets happy feet.
- Listen...

337
00:34:14,930 --> 00:34:17,057
...however he plays it, we play it straight.

338
00:34:17,140 --> 00:34:20,477
Isabella Zancona's involvement
remains classified.

339
00:34:20,936 --> 00:34:23,313
That means nothing in the report.

340
00:34:23,522 --> 00:34:26,274
No name, no location, nothing. Got it?

341
00:34:26,733 --> 00:34:28,068
Yes, sir.

342
00:34:32,656 --> 00:34:35,325
I never knew his name,
but he was definitely American.

343
00:34:35,409 --> 00:34:37,869
He had some kind
of special military training...

344
00:34:37,953 --> 00:34:40,997
...where he learned Spanish,
in El Salvador, I think.

345
00:34:41,289 --> 00:34:43,667
I didn't like talking to him.

346
00:34:43,750 --> 00:34:46,837
I suppose we were all dangerous people...

347
00:34:47,170 --> 00:34:49,548
...but he was different.

348
00:34:49,714 --> 00:34:53,385
Declan was fire, all passion.
He had a cause.

349
00:34:53,552 --> 00:34:57,139
This man was ice. No feeling, nothing.

350
00:34:57,722 --> 00:35:00,892
Okay. Thank you, Mrs. Decker.
You've been very helpful.

351
00:35:01,435 --> 00:35:06,189
It's best if you keep our conversation
confidential, even from your husband.

352
00:35:07,274 --> 00:35:09,151
Don't worry about George.

353
00:35:09,526 --> 00:35:13,029
He doesn't know anything
about my past and he doesn't want to.

354
00:35:13,113 --> 00:35:16,366
All he needs to know is that I love him.

355
00:35:19,786 --> 00:35:21,246
I see.

356
00:35:22,706 --> 00:35:24,541
I thank you again.

357
00:35:25,584 --> 00:35:27,544
I'll wait for you in the car.

358
00:35:35,469 --> 00:35:38,847
This opens a locker
at Norfolk Greyhound Terminal.

359
00:35:39,306 --> 00:35:43,059
Inside is a clean passport and $10,000 cash.

360
00:35:43,518 --> 00:35:46,897
Your friends left it with me
in case you ever showed up.

361
00:35:47,481 --> 00:35:50,734
Take it and go back to Ireland.

362
00:35:51,526 --> 00:35:53,028
I can't.

363
00:35:53,487 --> 00:35:55,155
What?

364
00:35:56,573 --> 00:35:58,825
You gave your word?

365
00:36:00,952 --> 00:36:02,662
Go now.

366
00:36:02,746 --> 00:36:06,041
Once he kills whoever he's after,
they'll send you back to prison.

367
00:36:06,124 --> 00:36:08,627
When I believe that, I'll use the key.

368
00:36:22,224 --> 00:36:24,142
Are you happy at least?

369
00:36:24,226 --> 00:36:27,312
Yes. I love my children.

370
00:36:28,855 --> 00:36:32,275
And my husband, in my way, I mean.

371
00:36:41,910 --> 00:36:46,415
Some nights I can close my eyes
and sleep...

372
00:36:49,126 --> 00:36:51,795
...and no dead faces come to wake me.

373
00:36:52,295 --> 00:36:54,714
That's more than I ever had.

374
00:36:57,426 --> 00:37:00,095
You wouldn't have me give that up,
would you?

375
00:37:04,099 --> 00:37:06,518
Give me some credit, will you?

376
00:37:39,384 --> 00:37:41,720
She's Basque, isn't she?

377
00:37:43,263 --> 00:37:44,681
Aye.

378
00:37:45,265 --> 00:37:47,809
They say Basques live by the vendetta.

379
00:37:48,435 --> 00:37:50,937
If they hate someone, it's to the death.

380
00:37:51,021 --> 00:37:53,398
It's the same way when they love.

381
00:37:56,735 --> 00:37:59,154
My first name is Valentina.

382
00:38:05,827 --> 00:38:07,871
You have family in Russia?

383
00:38:07,954 --> 00:38:10,999
My parents. My brother, in the navy.

384
00:38:11,083 --> 00:38:13,168
Husband? Kids?

385
00:38:13,585 --> 00:38:16,630
No. I have not found the time.

386
00:38:20,842 --> 00:38:24,763
In truth, it's never been a conflict for me.

387
00:38:24,971 --> 00:38:28,016
This is not a quality
a man looks for in a woman.

388
00:38:36,149 --> 00:38:37,442
By the way...

389
00:38:37,526 --> 00:38:40,237
...whatever Isabella gave you after I left...

390
00:38:40,487 --> 00:38:44,533
...I trust you won't use it
until after our business is concluded.

391
00:38:45,992 --> 00:38:47,953
Don't miss a thing, do you?

392
00:38:48,036 --> 00:38:50,080
No, Mr. Mulqueen.

393
00:38:50,831 --> 00:38:52,707
I see everything.

394
00:39:02,843 --> 00:39:06,012
Maybe we should start
by canceling your public appearances.

395
00:39:06,096 --> 00:39:08,890
No, I don't think that's necessary.
I mean, not yet.

396
00:39:08,974 --> 00:39:12,519
This fellow's gonna need to
make preparations. He'll need time.

397
00:39:12,602 --> 00:39:15,939
- How tight are the borders?
- Mexico and Canada have...

398
00:39:16,940 --> 00:39:20,694
Mr. Mulqueen?
Something you'd like to share?

399
00:39:21,862 --> 00:39:24,364
He'll likely be using four false identities.

400
00:39:24,448 --> 00:39:27,701
Three will be on him, and one
in reserve at a drop box somewhere.

401
00:39:27,784 --> 00:39:30,871
- That's the way he used to operate.
- What matter if he has 40?

402
00:39:30,954 --> 00:39:35,208
It's still one man. Might we not
be creating a storm in a tea cup?

403
00:39:35,292 --> 00:39:38,128
Exactly. I agree with you 100 percent.

404
00:39:39,212 --> 00:39:41,423
Director Bolitonov.

405
00:39:41,590 --> 00:39:45,343
Terek has always made
doing his own killing a point of honor.

406
00:39:45,552 --> 00:39:47,763
Usually very bloody and very public.

407
00:39:47,846 --> 00:39:49,890
A statement, if you will.

408
00:39:50,182 --> 00:39:52,768
So, if he's hired an outsider...

409
00:39:52,934 --> 00:39:56,104
...obviously, this is something
he takes very seriously.

410
00:39:56,188 --> 00:39:58,523
Until this Jackal is captured or killed...

411
00:39:58,607 --> 00:40:00,776
...I don't think we can afford to do any less.

412
00:40:00,859 --> 00:40:04,279
Come on. Let's get real here. It's one guy.

413
00:40:04,404 --> 00:40:07,199
It's just one guy. Bolitonov's right.

414
00:40:07,449 --> 00:40:10,452
With the assets in this room,
the guy's as good as got.

415
00:40:10,535 --> 00:40:12,871
That's if he doesn't blow it first...

416
00:40:12,954 --> 00:40:17,125
...like a lot of these clowns.
Remember that guy? What was his name?

417
00:40:18,627 --> 00:40:20,420
What's that, Mr. Mulqueen?

418
00:40:21,421 --> 00:40:24,633
I'm sorry, Mr. Brown,
but this man is no clown.

419
00:40:24,841 --> 00:40:27,260
He knows all your moves, back to front.

420
00:40:28,011 --> 00:40:30,430
Right now, you got a name.
That's all you got.

421
00:40:30,514 --> 00:40:33,850
The Jackal's got a target: You.
He's got a timetable.

422
00:40:33,934 --> 00:40:37,979
As to making mistakes, he's spent 20 years
in a trade that doesn't forgive error.

423
00:40:38,063 --> 00:40:40,190
And he's prevailed.

424
00:40:41,233 --> 00:40:43,819
You think he's the one
who is up against us?

425
00:40:43,944 --> 00:40:45,862
It's the other way around.

426
00:41:46,757 --> 00:41:48,675
- Hi.
- Hi.

427
00:41:50,302 --> 00:41:53,597
- Can I buy you a drink?
- Yeah.

428
00:42:06,693 --> 00:42:09,029
I think you should come home with me.

429
00:42:10,781 --> 00:42:12,449
I'd love to...

430
00:42:13,408 --> 00:42:15,327
...but I can't.

431
00:42:15,494 --> 00:42:17,329
I have to go back to Atlanta...

432
00:42:17,412 --> 00:42:20,165
...to finalize my very messy divorce.

433
00:42:22,626 --> 00:42:24,419
Does she know?

434
00:42:24,503 --> 00:42:26,421
She does now.

435
00:42:29,758 --> 00:42:31,676
So how am I gonna see you again?

436
00:42:31,760 --> 00:42:34,262
You could give me one of your cards.

437
00:42:40,852 --> 00:42:42,771
You're not gonna call.

438
00:42:42,938 --> 00:42:44,689
Douglas.

439
00:42:47,025 --> 00:42:50,570
You just have to have
a little faith in people, that's all.

440
00:42:50,904 --> 00:42:52,864
Like I do.

441
00:44:05,937 --> 00:44:07,731
Open your shirt.

442
00:44:10,150 --> 00:44:12,611
- Easy now. Easy.
- Now!

443
00:44:15,822 --> 00:44:17,616
Easy.

444
00:44:18,158 --> 00:44:19,951
Open your shirt.

445
00:44:20,035 --> 00:44:21,828
Easy now.

446
00:44:28,919 --> 00:44:31,671
Souvenirs of British hospitality.

447
00:44:37,344 --> 00:44:39,221
I apologize.

448
00:44:42,724 --> 00:44:43,975
No problem.

449
00:44:44,059 --> 00:44:48,480
Oslo Travel came up with a James William
Hayslip who flew from Toronto...

450
00:44:48,563 --> 00:44:51,316
...August 25, two days before
the meeting with Terek.

451
00:44:51,400 --> 00:44:55,821
We checked the Social Security number
on his passport, and guess what?

452
00:44:57,030 --> 00:45:01,910
It belongs to an inmate committed to a
mental institution in Virginia 12 years ago.

453
00:45:03,161 --> 00:45:05,622
Now, Canadian Travel says he flew...

454
00:45:05,705 --> 00:45:09,042
...to Montreal nine days ago.

455
00:45:56,715 --> 00:45:57,758
Hello?

456
00:45:59,176 --> 00:46:00,218
Hello?

457
00:46:00,302 --> 00:46:02,554
- Yeah?
- Yeah, Charlie Murdock.

458
00:46:02,804 --> 00:46:05,849
Picking up a delivery, eh?

459
00:46:06,850 --> 00:46:08,769
Invoice.

460
00:46:09,060 --> 00:46:10,854
Yes.

461
00:46:10,937 --> 00:46:13,648
- It's a hot one, eh?
- You can say that again.

462
00:47:16,503 --> 00:47:19,923
Hi. I need to use one of your computers.

463
00:47:20,715 --> 00:47:22,634
Sure. Any one.

464
00:47:27,222 --> 00:47:29,224
Can I get on line with this?

465
00:47:29,307 --> 00:47:31,226
Yeah, sure.

466
00:50:17,225 --> 00:50:19,436
Go check upstairs.

467
00:51:50,444 --> 00:51:52,362
Thank you.

468
00:51:52,779 --> 00:51:54,781
Hayslip's disappeared.

469
00:51:54,865 --> 00:51:58,493
Border Patrol has the passport photo,
but nothing's shown up yet.

470
00:51:58,577 --> 00:52:02,164
- He's moved on. I told you.
- One moment.

471
00:52:02,414 --> 00:52:05,250
The only place we're sure
he's been is Montreal.

472
00:52:05,500 --> 00:52:08,962
What if he started using
the next identity there?

473
00:52:09,463 --> 00:52:10,964
I'm not following you.

474
00:52:11,047 --> 00:52:13,925
Hayslip disappeared,
that doesn't mean the Jackal did.

475
00:52:14,009 --> 00:52:16,052
Perhaps something has happened.

476
00:52:17,554 --> 00:52:21,683
Witherspoon, have the Montreal police
check their logs for the last 48 hours.

477
00:52:21,767 --> 00:52:24,644
If he's on to the next name,
it's because it's in the plan.

478
00:52:24,728 --> 00:52:27,022
- A man like this doesn't make mistakes.
- No?

479
00:52:27,105 --> 00:52:29,691
They always make one, somewhere.

480
00:52:29,941 --> 00:52:32,277
Isn't that how you were caught?

481
00:52:43,705 --> 00:52:45,749
What's her story, then?

482
00:52:46,458 --> 00:52:48,335
Major Koslova...

483
00:52:48,877 --> 00:52:52,130
...ends the debate about
women in combat, as far as I'm concerned.

484
00:52:52,214 --> 00:52:53,632
How's that?

485
00:52:54,591 --> 00:52:57,803
When she saved my life
and took out Terek's brother...

486
00:52:58,386 --> 00:53:02,724
...she did it knowing she'd be drawing
a death sentence down on her own neck.

487
00:53:02,849 --> 00:53:07,562
But when we offered to set her up
someplace else when this is over...

488
00:53:07,646 --> 00:53:10,023
...you know what she said?

489
00:53:10,774 --> 00:53:13,693
"The good guys don't hide. "

490
00:53:16,571 --> 00:53:18,532
Fierce woman.

491
00:53:18,698 --> 00:53:22,160
In that country, under that system...

492
00:53:23,245 --> 00:53:25,205
Staggering.

493
00:53:28,542 --> 00:53:31,711
Oh, shit, you know what?
I couldn't get titanium.

494
00:53:31,795 --> 00:53:34,965
So, I had a friend mold the base
out of carbon fiber instead.

495
00:53:35,048 --> 00:53:38,135
Came in 23 kilos
under the weight you asked for.

496
00:53:38,218 --> 00:53:40,470
- Is that cool?
- Yeah, that's great.

497
00:53:41,096 --> 00:53:45,100
I'm still gonna want the plans, the mold
and the scrap material. Remember?

498
00:53:45,183 --> 00:53:47,519
Yeah.

499
00:53:49,146 --> 00:53:52,065
- Maybe we ought to talk about that.
- Oh?

500
00:53:56,570 --> 00:53:59,823
This rig, I figure it's to support
something pretty heavy, right?

501
00:54:00,240 --> 00:54:03,910
Like a Gatling gun, maybe?

502
00:54:04,828 --> 00:54:07,539
Or a 20-millimeter cannon?

503
00:54:07,622 --> 00:54:09,916
You must be shooting
at something pretty big.

504
00:54:10,000 --> 00:54:11,960
Armored car, maybe?

505
00:54:13,170 --> 00:54:14,629
Bank vault?

506
00:54:14,713 --> 00:54:18,967
I don't know. You could be shooting
a fucking airliner for all I know.

507
00:54:19,176 --> 00:54:21,303
But the point is...

508
00:54:21,720 --> 00:54:25,348
...a job like this
can attract a lot of attention.

509
00:54:27,058 --> 00:54:28,727
I don't want any attention.

510
00:54:28,810 --> 00:54:31,354
Right, right. That's why I'm saying...

511
00:54:31,813 --> 00:54:35,025
...I think the plans
and mold are worth a little bonus.

512
00:54:36,359 --> 00:54:38,445
- How much?
- I don't know.

513
00:54:39,821 --> 00:54:41,615
$100,000?

514
00:54:43,950 --> 00:54:48,205
Come on, man. You know it's worth it.
You got a serious piece of equipment.

515
00:54:57,589 --> 00:54:59,591
All right.

516
00:55:00,383 --> 00:55:02,427
I'll get you $50,000 tomorrow.

517
00:55:03,095 --> 00:55:07,057
I'm gonna need a place to test this.
Someplace that won't draw any attention.

518
00:55:07,140 --> 00:55:10,602
We got a place like that.
We got a place just like that.

519
00:55:26,660 --> 00:55:31,081
Target's in place.
Man, I should have brought some beer.

520
00:55:36,420 --> 00:55:39,798
Motherfuckin' motherfucker.

521
00:55:40,715 --> 00:55:44,719
That motherfucker is state of the art!

522
00:55:45,345 --> 00:55:49,850
I knew it was gonna be big. I didn't know
it was gonna be the prototype cannon.

523
00:55:50,058 --> 00:55:52,644
It's a fucking mole.

524
00:55:54,104 --> 00:55:57,274
- Some hairy-looking rounds.
- Made from depleted uranium.

525
00:55:57,357 --> 00:55:59,109
It'll go through anything.

526
00:55:59,192 --> 00:56:01,445
Once they get inside, they just spall.

527
00:56:01,528 --> 00:56:03,655
Hell, yeah. They spall?

528
00:56:04,239 --> 00:56:06,908
They get in there, and they just...

529
00:56:07,784 --> 00:56:08,994
That rocks.

530
00:56:09,077 --> 00:56:11,747
- Look at the lens on that thing.
- Don't touch that.

531
00:56:11,830 --> 00:56:14,750
It's got, like, a 2,000-mile zoom lens.

532
00:56:15,333 --> 00:56:17,169
That thing is kick-ass.

533
00:56:17,669 --> 00:56:20,213
Dude, is this thing a prototype, or what?

534
00:56:20,672 --> 00:56:23,884
I bet you it cost you a shitload.
That rocks.

535
00:56:25,051 --> 00:56:26,511
Man, you rock.

536
00:56:26,595 --> 00:56:28,805
Do you know what I'm saying?

537
00:56:28,889 --> 00:56:31,141
Rock!

538
00:56:33,351 --> 00:56:35,562
Fucking thing kicks ass.

539
00:56:48,408 --> 00:56:50,952
Bring on the spall, baby.

540
00:56:51,495 --> 00:56:53,914
- I can't wait to see the fuck...
- Lamont.

541
00:56:54,956 --> 00:56:56,708
Close your mouth.

542
00:57:09,888 --> 00:57:12,182
Smooth action, yeah?

543
00:57:33,203 --> 00:57:34,830
Ready?

544
00:57:41,002 --> 00:57:44,172
Yeah! Spall!

545
00:57:51,513 --> 00:57:52,931
Well, at least...

546
00:57:53,723 --> 00:57:56,351
...it took out the target.
- No, it's off...

547
00:57:56,893 --> 00:57:58,895
...by at least three millimeters.

548
00:57:58,979 --> 00:58:02,065
No, dude. That's precision craftsmanship.

549
00:58:02,315 --> 00:58:05,068
- It isn't off by three millimeters.
- So, Lamont...

550
00:58:06,653 --> 00:58:09,656
...tell me how you sight
in this thing automatically.

551
00:58:09,740 --> 00:58:13,326
Punch in the windage and
the elevation you want and hit enter.

552
00:58:13,785 --> 00:58:17,748
- So you just kind of guestimate it, huh?
- Basically guestimation.

553
00:58:20,292 --> 00:58:21,960
And hit enter.

554
00:58:27,758 --> 00:58:29,676
I give up!

555
00:58:31,511 --> 00:58:33,930
- I guess the automatic sighting works.
- Yeah.

556
00:58:34,014 --> 00:58:37,434
- I thought I was about to sprawl.
- Well, Lamont...

557
00:58:37,517 --> 00:58:40,520
...gonna have to speed-test it now.
- Speed test.

558
00:58:41,188 --> 00:58:43,356
So, run.

559
00:58:48,904 --> 00:58:50,781
What do you mean?

560
00:58:51,823 --> 00:58:55,077
I mean run, now.

561
00:59:10,258 --> 00:59:12,177
Run to your right!

562
00:59:40,914 --> 00:59:42,916
Get up!

563
00:59:45,419 --> 00:59:48,088
All right, good! Stop there!

564
00:59:49,589 --> 00:59:51,508
Just stop there!

565
00:59:51,800 --> 00:59:53,760
Turn around!

566
00:59:54,803 --> 00:59:57,097
Hold out that pack of cigarettes!

567
01:00:00,684 --> 01:00:02,811
Don't be afraid!

568
01:00:08,692 --> 01:00:10,777
Stand very still!

569
01:00:21,037 --> 01:00:22,998
Stand still!

570
01:00:39,222 --> 01:00:41,475
I told you it was off.

571
01:00:44,019 --> 01:00:46,563
Move over by the car!

572
01:00:47,147 --> 01:00:49,816
Quick, before you pass out!

573
01:01:42,953 --> 01:01:45,831
Here we go, sir. Major. Mac.

574
01:01:46,248 --> 01:01:50,710
Eleven days ago, Charles C. Murdock
bought himself a new Dodge minivan.

575
01:01:52,379 --> 01:01:54,714
That was a big surprise to Mr. Murdock...

576
01:01:54,798 --> 01:01:59,052
...whose passport and wallet were stolen
16 days ago at the Helsinki airport.

577
01:01:59,136 --> 01:02:00,512
Anything from the border?

578
01:02:00,595 --> 01:02:03,515
We sent a description of the van
from here to Manitoba.

579
01:02:03,598 --> 01:02:07,853
I have something. Uphall Station.
It's a small town outside Ottawa.

580
01:02:07,936 --> 01:02:10,856
- I think your man has been there.
- Let's go.

581
01:02:26,830 --> 01:02:29,916
The owner is Ian Lamont, small-time hood.

582
01:02:30,041 --> 01:02:32,377
The coroner has what's left of him
at Broxburn.

583
01:02:32,461 --> 01:02:35,046
We get the idea. Let's get to the shop.

584
01:02:44,723 --> 01:02:47,100
Hello. Think I got something here.

585
01:02:53,398 --> 01:02:55,192
What is it?

586
01:02:55,567 --> 01:02:57,527
This is a remote firing station.

587
01:02:57,611 --> 01:02:59,529
See, it maneuvers a weapon.

588
01:02:59,613 --> 01:03:03,742
The servos run off a remote control,
like a model airplane.

589
01:03:03,867 --> 01:03:06,453
We used to make these things
for mortars or...

590
01:03:06,536 --> 01:03:09,581
...such but nothing like this size.

591
01:03:09,998 --> 01:03:12,000
He needs a van just to move it around.

592
01:03:12,084 --> 01:03:14,503
What would something this size
be used for?

593
01:03:14,586 --> 01:03:17,339
- Antiaircraft?
- No, you can buy a mount for that.

594
01:03:17,422 --> 01:03:20,050
A missile's the best thing for an aircraft.

595
01:03:20,675 --> 01:03:25,055
- No, this is for something else entirely.
- Something with one hell of a range.

596
01:03:25,180 --> 01:03:27,265
Not just the range, though.

597
01:03:27,516 --> 01:03:30,102
See, if it is a gun, it's the cyclic rate.

598
01:03:30,727 --> 01:03:35,065
You can send off a hundred bullets
before the first one ever hits the target.

599
01:03:39,653 --> 01:03:41,947
Good thing about a boat like this
is it sells itself.

600
01:03:42,030 --> 01:03:45,325
It's a hell of a lot of boat for the money.
It's got radar...

601
01:03:45,409 --> 01:03:49,579
...GPS, autopilot, auto-furling.
You can take this baby out by yourself.

602
01:03:51,164 --> 01:03:55,377
This has even got a cellular phone.
You can call your wife if you want to.

603
01:03:56,503 --> 01:03:58,797
So, what do you think?

604
01:03:59,339 --> 01:04:01,508
"Deja Vu. "

605
01:04:04,386 --> 01:04:06,346
She's perfect.

606
01:05:50,617 --> 01:05:52,202
- Yes?
- Jackal.

607
01:05:52,285 --> 01:05:53,995
They know about Hayslip.

608
01:05:54,079 --> 01:05:58,375
They know you were in Canada,
and they have an Irishman helping them.

609
01:05:58,458 --> 01:06:01,128
- Irishman's name?
- Mulqueen.

610
01:06:02,754 --> 01:06:05,674
- Declan Mulqueen?
- Declan Mulqueen.

611
01:06:08,885 --> 01:06:10,971
The operation's still a go.

612
01:06:14,099 --> 01:06:15,142
Declan.

613
01:06:15,225 --> 01:06:19,521
Every crossing point and airport has
his photograph, but RCMP has nothing.

614
01:06:19,604 --> 01:06:22,774
Our Border Patrol,
the INS are both on the highest alert.

615
01:06:22,858 --> 01:06:24,401
Again, nothing.

616
01:06:24,484 --> 01:06:28,196
Let's face it, you don't have to be Houdini
to make it across from Canada.

617
01:06:28,280 --> 01:06:32,242
- He probably walked across.
- He won't be walking, I can tell you that.

618
01:06:32,492 --> 01:06:34,119
He's got a weapon to move.

619
01:06:34,411 --> 01:06:37,789
- What kind of patrols do you have here?
- The Great Lakes?

620
01:06:37,873 --> 01:06:39,708
Not a lot. No need.

621
01:06:39,791 --> 01:06:41,710
People either drive or fly.

622
01:06:42,002 --> 01:06:45,714
There are a few ferry services,
but we checked those out as well.

623
01:06:46,131 --> 01:06:47,924
What about people with boats?

624
01:06:48,008 --> 01:06:50,302
What kind of immigration controls
do you have?

625
01:06:50,385 --> 01:06:53,472
Arriving vessels have to
check with the harbormaster.

626
01:06:53,555 --> 01:06:57,267
- Voluntarily?
- Yeah. No active enforcement.

627
01:06:59,436 --> 01:07:02,898
Say he does use a boat,
he'll still want to mix with others.

628
01:07:03,857 --> 01:07:06,193
Are there many gatherings to speak of?

629
01:07:06,485 --> 01:07:08,695
Yeah, the Mackinaw Regatta
is going on now.

630
01:07:08,779 --> 01:07:12,115
- It's the biggest regatta on Lake Michigan.
- From where to where?

631
01:07:12,199 --> 01:07:15,994
It starts in Mackinaw
and it ends in Chicago.

632
01:08:24,271 --> 01:08:27,107
Witherspoon, take Waveland.

633
01:08:27,190 --> 01:08:29,693
Declan, Valentina: Chicago Yacht Club.

634
01:08:29,943 --> 01:08:32,320
I'll take the locals. And remember...

635
01:08:32,404 --> 01:08:36,616
...it'll be an Ontario boat if it's here.
Look at everything and stay on your radios.

636
01:08:36,700 --> 01:08:40,954
If you do find something, call in backup.
I want an arrest, not a firefight.

637
01:08:46,376 --> 01:08:48,503
All right, let's get to it.

638
01:08:50,589 --> 01:08:53,800
Preston, what about
letting me have a gun?

639
01:08:54,593 --> 01:08:56,052
Are you crazy?

640
01:08:56,136 --> 01:09:01,433
If the right people knew I was letting you
walk around I'd get forced retirement.

641
01:09:03,518 --> 01:09:05,520
No fucking gun.

642
01:09:09,357 --> 01:09:12,903
- So many people.
- So many rich people.

643
01:09:13,070 --> 01:09:14,780
Shall we dance?

644
01:09:15,697 --> 01:09:17,699
He wouldn't give me a gun.

645
01:10:14,339 --> 01:10:15,590
He is hot.

646
01:10:17,092 --> 01:10:19,177
He's mine. Back off.

647
01:10:23,140 --> 01:10:25,100
Hey, you want some champagne?

648
01:10:25,183 --> 01:10:27,894
- Come on. Join us.
- Maybe later.

649
01:10:27,978 --> 01:10:29,813
Join us.

650
01:12:16,545 --> 01:12:18,296
Declan!

651
01:12:50,954 --> 01:12:52,497
Get out of the way!

652
01:13:15,479 --> 01:13:18,190
Preston, can I talk to you?

653
01:13:22,235 --> 01:13:24,321
Look, he saw me. He wasn't surprised.

654
01:13:24,404 --> 01:13:26,198
Like he was expecting me.

655
01:13:26,281 --> 01:13:28,658
One of your team
is playing for the other side.

656
01:13:28,742 --> 01:13:30,744
I can vouch for every man on this team.

657
01:13:30,827 --> 01:13:33,580
- You've got a traitor.
- This is not the IRA.

658
01:13:33,663 --> 01:13:36,500
- We don't get infiltrators.
- Somebody got to him.

659
01:13:37,667 --> 01:13:41,755
This is a manhunt, not your cause.
Don't make it personal.

660
01:13:42,339 --> 01:13:44,716
What do you fucking know?

661
01:13:54,101 --> 01:13:55,811
I'll tell you what I know.

662
01:13:55,894 --> 01:13:59,106
I know the Jackal set you up
in that arms deal in Libya.

663
01:13:59,356 --> 01:14:02,734
I know Isabella was wounded
when you walked into the trap.

664
01:14:03,235 --> 01:14:05,987
I also know that it was
the business you had chosen.

665
01:14:06,071 --> 01:14:09,574
Did you also know that Isabella
was pregnant when she got shot?

666
01:14:09,658 --> 01:14:11,910
That our child didn't survive?

667
01:14:16,456 --> 01:14:19,334
Don't tell me it's not personal, Mr. Preston.

668
01:14:22,003 --> 01:14:24,881
I can't let you jeopardize us in a vendetta.

669
01:14:25,048 --> 01:14:26,967
There's no vendetta.

670
01:14:27,384 --> 01:14:30,595
All I hope for is a fresh start, you know?

671
01:14:36,685 --> 01:14:38,979
Maybe it'll happen.

672
01:16:09,069 --> 01:16:11,530
This was recorded at 1:00 a. m.

673
01:16:11,613 --> 01:16:15,033
It's a call to a number
in Brighton Beach, New York.

674
01:16:16,451 --> 01:16:17,744
Item four:

675
01:16:17,828 --> 01:16:21,748
At 1:05 p. m. Director Brown
is scheduled to meet the First Lady...

676
01:16:21,832 --> 01:16:24,084
...at a reception at the White House...

677
01:16:24,167 --> 01:16:26,711
...regarding the New Hope Hospital
opening.

678
01:16:26,795 --> 01:16:29,131
Other participants will be decided...

679
01:16:31,383 --> 01:16:33,802
That information came out of this room.

680
01:16:36,346 --> 01:16:39,391
Who? Whose voice is it on that tape?

681
01:16:46,314 --> 01:16:48,275
Mine.

682
01:16:52,279 --> 01:16:53,989
Mr. Ambassador.

683
01:16:54,072 --> 01:16:56,700
We have arranged to hold
a flight to Moscow.

684
01:16:56,783 --> 01:17:00,162
A car is waiting to drive
Colonel Bolitonov to the airport.

685
01:17:17,054 --> 01:17:19,306
How did you know whose phone to tap?

686
01:17:19,389 --> 01:17:23,226
I didn't, so I tapped everybody's.

687
01:17:24,186 --> 01:17:27,314
But I have diplomatic immunity.

688
01:17:27,814 --> 01:17:30,484
Who authorized you to tap my telephone?

689
01:17:30,567 --> 01:17:32,152
I did, Ambassador.

690
01:17:32,235 --> 01:17:36,198
We're currently examining documents
taken from Bolitonov's apartment.

691
01:17:52,464 --> 01:17:54,382
Get me a helicopter.

692
01:18:21,701 --> 01:18:23,286
Jackal.

693
01:18:23,495 --> 01:18:27,416
Director Bolitonov
is no longer contactable at this number.

694
01:18:27,624 --> 01:18:30,001
All inquiries should be forwarded to...

695
01:18:35,841 --> 01:18:39,469
This is only a precaution for a short while,
until we get this man.

696
01:18:39,553 --> 01:18:41,972
You and your family
will be safer in Washington.

697
01:18:42,055 --> 01:18:44,516
You really think you'll find him?
You won't.

698
01:18:44,599 --> 01:18:47,811
- Believe me, you can't.
- It's our job to try.

699
01:18:47,894 --> 01:18:51,314
And waste your time
and maybe get killed for nothing?

700
01:18:53,775 --> 01:18:55,193
I began this.

701
01:18:55,318 --> 01:18:59,448
I have to do what I can,
so please get your family away.

702
01:19:05,829 --> 01:19:07,372
Let's go.

703
01:19:23,805 --> 01:19:24,890
Everything okay?

704
01:19:24,973 --> 01:19:29,853
Valentina's evacuating Isabella and her
family in case he knows where she lives.

705
01:19:32,773 --> 01:19:35,734
Look, the director doesn't even know
where Isabella lives.

706
01:19:35,817 --> 01:19:39,988
I ordered Witherspoon to keep her
out of the report. No way Jackal knows.

707
01:19:40,405 --> 01:19:44,618
Well, our Russian black-heart surely passed
everything else to him, didn't he?

708
01:19:44,701 --> 01:19:46,536
Here, look.

709
01:19:48,830 --> 01:19:51,708
That's your phone number.
That's Valentina's.

710
01:19:51,792 --> 01:19:54,002
You know those two at the bottom?

711
01:19:57,297 --> 01:19:59,549
The first one's the Russian Embassy.

712
01:20:01,009 --> 01:20:02,969
The second one's...

713
01:20:05,430 --> 01:20:08,058
- Son of a bitch.
- What?

714
01:20:09,559 --> 01:20:12,354
This is an FBI access code.

715
01:20:17,818 --> 01:20:20,862
- FBI Data Center.
- This is Special Agent Carter Preston.

716
01:20:20,946 --> 01:20:24,866
- My authorization number is 223578-Kilo.
- Shit!

717
01:20:24,950 --> 01:20:29,663
I need a voice transcription of field report
November Alpha from 9-15 this year.

718
01:20:29,746 --> 01:20:33,583
Agent filing: Witherspoon, Timothy I.
And I'm in a hurry, operator.

719
01:20:38,130 --> 01:20:40,090
I shouldn't have trusted you.

720
01:20:42,759 --> 01:20:45,095
Field report November Alpha...

721
01:20:45,262 --> 01:20:48,014
...filed 9:00 a. M...
- Scroll.

722
01:20:48,223 --> 01:20:52,436
To perform interview of subject
Isabella Zancona at the following address...

723
01:20:52,519 --> 01:20:55,480
Witherspoon, you by-the-book asshole!

724
01:21:12,789 --> 01:21:14,708
I'm gonna check upstairs.

725
01:21:14,916 --> 01:21:16,918
Witherspoon?

726
01:21:42,486 --> 01:21:44,196
Witherspoon?

727
01:21:53,914 --> 01:21:55,624
Witherspoon?

728
01:22:10,013 --> 01:22:11,723
Come out!

729
01:22:12,349 --> 01:22:14,059
Please don't shoot me.

730
01:22:15,560 --> 01:22:17,479
Just taking out the garbage.

731
01:22:18,772 --> 01:22:20,774
- I got one more trip.
- Hurry.

732
01:22:20,857 --> 01:22:24,069
- We'll meet you at the front.
- Yes, ma'am.

733
01:22:32,369 --> 01:22:35,789
All locked up. Where's Witherspoon?

734
01:22:35,872 --> 01:22:38,458
He's in the backyard, taking out the trash.

735
01:22:41,086 --> 01:22:43,422
It's coming from the back. Let's go!

736
01:22:58,395 --> 01:23:01,231
- Where is it coming from?
- I don't know.

737
01:23:26,798 --> 01:23:29,051
Set to go off two minutes ago.

738
01:23:30,510 --> 01:23:32,512
What the hell?

739
01:23:34,181 --> 01:23:36,141
Where's McMurphy?

740
01:25:36,219 --> 01:25:40,098
Press here, hard. It'll slow the bleeding.

741
01:25:53,403 --> 01:25:55,739
See, that's bad.

742
01:25:56,323 --> 01:25:59,785
Blood's almost black.
That means the bullet's in your liver.

743
01:26:00,285 --> 01:26:02,454
You got about 20 minutes to live.

744
01:26:03,330 --> 01:26:06,625
If the pain gets too much,
you can take your hand away...

